{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17604427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17604427"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:53:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:53:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15828"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15828"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.07,0.04,0.61,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8519"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71475"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8519"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15828"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56984"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8574"},{"type":"tags","id":"8599"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20454"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20464"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71475"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early embryonic development, cells organise into three primary germ layers through gastrulation. Each germ layer gives rise to specific tissues and organs in the developing embryo.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures develops from the embryonic endoderm?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blood vessels and heart","Neural tube","Skin and hair follicles","Epithelial lining of the respiratory tract","Vertebrae and ribs"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eepithelial lining of the respiratory tract\u003C/strong\u003E develops from the embryonic endoderm, along with the epithelial lining of the digestive tract and its associated organs including the liver, gallbladder, and pancreas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options develop from other germ layers:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood vessels and heart\u003C/strong\u003E - develops from mesoderm (specifically splanchnic mesoderm)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeural tube\u003C/strong\u003E - develops from ectoderm through neurulation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkin and hair follicles\u003C/strong\u003E - develop from ectoderm\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVertebrae and ribs\u003C/strong\u003E - develop from mesoderm (specifically paraxial mesoderm)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEach germ layer forms distinct tissue types: endoderm forms internal epithelial linings, mesoderm forms connective tissues and muscle, and ectoderm forms nervous tissue and external coverings.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The endoderm forms the epithelial lining of the respiratory and digestive tracts, plus associated organs like liver and pancreas","The mesoderm forms muscle, bone, blood vessels and connective tissue","The ectoderm forms the nervous system, epidermis and its derivatives"],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56984"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15828"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56984"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T18:16:25+10:30","updatedAt":"20